rtigung, also der Frage nach dem Grund und der Grenze des dem Staat geschuldeten Gehorsams, vor dem Hintergrund der konfessionellen Bürgerkriege und der Suprematieansprüche des Papsttums über die weltlichen Fürsten. Hier wurden erstmals auch die im vatikanischen Geheimarchiv und in der Vatikanbibliothek aufbewahrten Quellen zu Barclay herangezogen.  aThis interdisciplinary doctoral thesis examines John Barclay's (1582-1621) New Latin romance "Argenis" (1621), a political roman-à-clef set against the background of the French religious wars. It is at once a pamphlet against the monarchomachists, a treatise on the "ideal ruler", and a manifesto of political absolutism. The interpretation studies the romance in the context of the political thinking of its author and looks closely at those medieval and early modern works on politics and statesmanship that marked Barclay's thinking. This study is also the first to draw on Vatican sources pertaining to Barclay.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 4aAbsolutismus. 4aBarclay, John / Argenis. 4aUtopie. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Social Sciences 1990 - 1999z9783110637939oZDB-23-GSS0 cprintz978348436548340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311093054240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110930542423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110930542/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-GSSc1990d1999